        <div class="text-top-div">
          <div class="markdown"><span><p><strong>Your Geometric Explanation (4.3):</strong></p>
<blockquote>
<p>Eigenvectors are special vectors that keep the same direction after a matrix transformation is applied. 
When a matrix acts on an eigenvector, it only changes the vector’s length, not its direction.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>The eigenvalue tells how much the vector is stretched or squished:</p>
<ul>
<li>If the eigenvalue is greater than 1, the vector is stretched.</li>
<li>If the eigenvalue is between 0 and 1, the vector is squished (shrunk).</li>
<li>If the eigenvalue is negative, the vector also flips direction.</li>
</ul>
<p>Geometrically, a matrix transformation can rotate, stretch, compress, or reflect vectors in space, but eigenvectors are the directions that remain unchanged except for scaling.</p>
</span></div>
        </div>
      </div>

