        <div class="text-top-div">
          <div class="markdown"><span><p><strong>SVD → PCA Connection (4.4):</strong></p>
<blockquote>
<p>SVD (Singular Value Decomposition) breaks a matrix into three parts:</p>
</blockquote>
<ul>
<li>U: directions of variation in the data</li>
<li>S: singular values representing the importance/strength of each direction</li>
<li>Vt: principal directions (features)</li>
</ul>
<p>PCA (Principal Component Analysis) is closely related to SVD. 
In PCA, the principal components are obtained from the singular vectors, and the singular values indicate how much variance each component explains.</p>
<p>The largest singular values correspond to the most important patterns in the data. 
A rank-1 approximation keeps only the strongest pattern, which is similar to keeping only the first principal component in PCA.</p>
</span></div>
        </div>
      </div>

