rtical" style="position: absolute;"><div class="slider" style="position: absolute; top: 0px; left: 0px; width: 10px; transform: translate3d(0px, 0px, 0px); contain: strict;"></div></div><div class="shadow"></div><div class="shadow"></div><div class="shadow"></div></div></div></div></div><div data-mprt="5" class="overflowingOverlayWidgets"></div><div class=".in-cell-overflowing"><div widgetid="editor.contrib.quickInputWidget" style="position: absolute; right: 50%; top: 0px;"></div></div></div></div></div>
        <div class="text-top-div">
          <div class="markdown"><span><p><strong>Concept Drift vs Covariate Drift &amp; PSI Thresholds (5.5):</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Concept drift:</strong>  A change in the relationship between input features and the target variable, meaning the same inputs start producing different outputs over time.</li>
<li><strong>Covariate drift:</strong>  A change in the distribution of input features while the relationship between features and target remains unchanged.</li>
<li><strong>PSI &lt; 0.1:</strong> Indicates the distribution is stable with no meaningful shift between training and production data.</li>
<li><strong>PSI 0.1–0.2:</strong> Indicates a moderate or minor shift that may require monitoring but not immediate action.</li>
<li><strong>PSI &gt; 0.2:</strong> Indicates a major distribution shift, suggesting significant instability between training and production data.</li>
<li><strong>Retraining trigger example:</strong>  A model is retrained when the PSI for critical input features exceeds 0.2 for multiple consecutive monitoring periods, or when production performance (e.g., accuracy drops by more than 5% or RMSE increases significantly compared to validation performance) indicates degradation.</li>
</ul>
</span></div>
        </div>
      </div>

